metadata.name: Bardez #99
metadata.description:
Bardez is the Armenian word for garden. It is etymologically tied to an ancient word for paradise, but that link goes deeper than etymology. Gardens have always been small pieces of paradise for me, and hearing the word in Armenian triggers a flood of warm memories.

Memories of wandering around my grandfather’s garden, plucking ripe plums and figs from their branches.
Memories of playing in my parents yard, the scent of jasmine in the summer heat.
Of sun warmed tomatoes in my mom’s vegetable patch.
The smell of dirt and grass.
Mud on my hands.
Sun on my skin.
Memories of paradise.

I hope you enjoy these gardens I’ve planted, and I hope they remind you of some warm and wonderful memories.
 
Nat Sarkissian






Notes:
 - This piece uses a shader to compute the lighting of the terrain in the first frame. If you don’t have a graphics card, you may have difficulty running this.

 - Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you the progress of the render, and also show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

 - Finally, collectors at the highest tier will be entitled to a signed print of their edition. For further details and updates, keep an eye on my Twitter (@_NatSarkissian).

metadata.name: Improvisation I #44
metadata.description:
“Improvisation I“ was born after my experiments with Fractal Brownian Motion. 

During random tweaks of colours, parameters and sizes I got something that really clicked with me — a picture I wanted to get out of the code some time ago. 

Painterly looking curves and blots with subtle colours transitions create a calming picture, sometimes resembling outlines of a landscape.

——————

To change the size of an image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6800 max.)]’ to the end of the URL. 
Press [C] to load a clean version without grain.
Press [S] to save the image.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Oct. 2022.

metadata.name: Commune #50
metadata.description:
A minimalist composition with a nod towards architecture.

2932 bytes of Vanilla JS.

For more info, see article linked below: Me, Commune, Etc.

In live mode:
’S’ : save as svg (without grain)
‘P’ : save as png (3780x2673)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=w’ : wood grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 7560 × 5346 (Chrome only)

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.description:
Play with lines

metadata.name: sketch: cairn() #22
metadata.description:
A cairn is a monument made of stacked rocks. In modern times, often used for wayfinding in remote areas, as in mountaineering, or to indicate an area of significance.

In this sketch I imagine these monuments -- through the looking glass. Paying mind to the simplicity of their construction, as well as the mysticism of what each might represent.

---

Sketch is a series meant to celebrate learning and experimentation.

In this sketch I experiment with subdivision, smoothing, textures, multiple levels of domain warping, and illustration techniques.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press s to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at size

metadata.name: Primordial #140
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

metadata.name: looking through a glass #18
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

generative art created by mehno using p5js
